WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.827 --> 00:00:13.870
Host: <i>And that's your biggest worry?</i>

2
00:00:13.954 --> 00:00:15.139
Dr. Schoenheiss:
<i>Yes. any kind of virus.</i>

3
00:00:15.163 --> 00:00:16.474
<i>but most probably
something similar</i>

4
00:00:16.498 --> 00:00:17.207
<i>to influenza.</i>

5
00:00:17.290 --> 00:00:18.625
Host: <i>Because of air travel.</i>

6
00:00:18.709 --> 00:00:19.769
Schoenheiss: <i>Through the air.</i>

7
00:00:19.793 --> 00:00:21.336
- Coughing...
- Uh. I-I'm sorry.

8
00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:23.130
I meant people.
On planes.

9
00:00:23.213 --> 00:00:24.816
Uh. that was something
you described in your book.

10
00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:26.760
Schoenheiss: Yes. a new
virus in Madagascar. say.

11
00:00:26.842 --> 00:00:28.927
could be in Chicago
within a matter of weeks.

12
00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:30.988
And we end up with a global
pandemic. Pan meaning "all."

13
00:00:31.012 --> 00:00:34.266
The whole world
becomes sick all at once.

14
00:00:34.349 --> 00:00:36.560
Hm... and. uh.
Dr. Neuman.

15
00:00:36.643 --> 00:00:38.103
you're also an epidemiologist.

16
00:00:38.186 --> 00:00:40.313
I presume the prospect
of a viral pandemic

17
00:00:40.397 --> 00:00:40.731
keeps you up at night as well.

18
00:00:40.814 --> 00:00:42.524
- No.
- No?

19
00:00:42.607 --> 00:00:44.276
- No.
- All right. well. that's our show.

20
00:00:44.359 --> 00:00:45.944
- (audience laughs)
- No.

21
00:00:46.027 --> 00:00:48.280
Mankind has been at war
with the virus from the start.

22
00:00:48.363 --> 00:00:50.699
Sometimes. millions of
people die. as in an actual war.

23
00:00:50.782 --> 00:00:53.118
But in the end. we always win.

24
00:00:53.201 --> 00:00:56.079
Uh. but you... Uh. just to
be clear. you. you do think

25
00:00:56.163 --> 00:00:57.456
microorganisms pose a threat.

26
00:00:57.539 --> 00:00:59.875
Oh. in the most dire terms.

27
00:00:59.958 --> 00:01:01.585
- Bacteria.
- No.

28
00:01:01.668 --> 00:01:02.461
- You like saying no.
- Yes.

29
00:01:02.544 --> 00:01:04.838
(audience laughs)

30
00:01:04.921 --> 00:01:06.882
Not bacteria.
Not viruses.

31
00:01:06.965 --> 00:01:08.884
- So?
- Fungus.

32
00:01:08.967 --> 00:01:10.635
(audience murmurs)

33
00:01:10.719 --> 00:01:12.471
Yes. that's the usual response.

34
00:01:12.554 --> 00:01:14.222
Fungi seem harmless enough.

35
00:01:14.306 --> 00:01:15.366
Many species know otherwise.

36
00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:19.436
Because there are some
fungi who seek not to kill...

37
00:01:19.519 --> 00:01:20.771
but to control.

38
00:01:20.854 --> 00:01:22.147
Let me ask you.

39
00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:23.648
where do we get LSD from?

40
00:01:23.732 --> 00:01:25.572
- Where do you get it from?
- (audience laughs)

41
00:01:25.650 --> 00:01:27.694
Dr. Neuman: It comes
from ergot. a fungus.

42
00:01:27.778 --> 00:01:30.197
Psilocybin?
Also a fungus.

43
00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:30.989
Viruses can make us ill.

44
00:01:31.072 --> 00:01:34.201
but fungi can alter
our very minds.

45
00:01:34.284 --> 00:01:36.244
There's a fungus
that infects insects.

46
00:01:36.328 --> 00:01:37.954
Gets inside an ant. for example.

47
00:01:38.038 --> 00:01:41.583
travels through its circulatory
system to the ant's brain.

48
00:01:41.666 --> 00:01:43.627
and then floods it
with hallucinogens.

49
00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:46.963
thus bending the ant's
mind to its will.

50
00:01:47.047 --> 00:01:48.887
The fungus starts to
direct the ant's behavior.

51
00:01:48.924 --> 00:01:50.634
telling it where to go.
what to do.

52
00:01:50.717 --> 00:01:52.761
like a puppeteer
with a marionette.

53
00:01:52.844 --> 00:01:54.262
And it gets worse.

54
00:01:54.346 --> 00:01:55.180
The fungus needs food to live.

55
00:01:55.263 --> 00:01:59.226
so it begins to devour
its host from within.

56
00:01:59.309 --> 00:02:00.977
replacing the ant's flesh
with its own.

57
00:02:01.061 --> 00:02:03.688
but it doesn't
let its victim die.

58
00:02:03.772 --> 00:02:06.817
No. it... it keeps
its puppet alive

59
00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:08.902
by preventing decomposition.

60
00:02:08.985 --> 00:02:11.571
How? Where do we
get penicillin from?

61
00:02:11.655 --> 00:02:14.074
- (quickly) Fungus.
- Oh...

62
00:02:14.157 --> 00:02:15.259
Dr. Schoenheiss.
you're in distress.

63
00:02:15.283 --> 00:02:16.785
Fungal infection
of this kind is real.

64
00:02:16.868 --> 00:02:18.370
but not in humans.

65
00:02:18.453 --> 00:02:20.247
True. fungi cannot survive

66
00:02:20.330 --> 00:02:23.250
if its host's internal
temperature is over 94 degrees.

67
00:02:23.333 --> 00:02:26.878
And currently. there are no
reasons for fungi to evolve

68
00:02:26.962 --> 00:02:28.356
to be able to withstand
higher temperatures.

69
00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:29.673
But what if that were to change?

70
00:02:29.756 --> 00:02:32.717
What if... for instance.

71
00:02:32.801 --> 00:02:35.637
the world were
to get slightly warmer?

72
00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:38.890
Well. now there is
reason to evolve.

73
00:02:38.974 --> 00:02:43.228
One gene mutates and an
ascomycete. uh. candida. ergot.

74
00:02:43.311 --> 00:02:46.273
cordyceps. aspergillus.
any one of them could become

75
00:02:46.356 --> 00:02:47.667
capable of burrowing
into our brains

76
00:02:47.691 --> 00:02:52.237
and taking control not of
millions of us. but billions of us.

77
00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:55.657
Billions of puppets
with poisoned minds

78
00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:58.410
permanently fixed
on one unifying goal:

79
00:02:58.493 --> 00:03:02.914
To spread the infection
to every last human alive

80
00:03:02.998 --> 00:03:04.374
by any means necessary.

81
00:03:04.457 --> 00:03:05.083
And there are no
treatments for this.

82
00:03:05.166 --> 00:03:08.378
No preventatives. no cures.

83
00:03:08.461 --> 00:03:10.213
They don't exist.
It's not even possible

84
00:03:10.297 --> 00:03:12.591
to make them.

85
00:03:12.674 --> 00:03:15.677
So if that happens?

86
00:03:16.177 --> 00:03:17.721
We lose.

87
00:03:19.139 --> 00:03:20.599
(host clears throat)

88
00:03:20.682 --> 00:03:22.934
Uh. we'll be back.

89
00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:28.356
(pensive theme music plays)

90
00:03:49.753 --> 00:03:51.796
♪ ♪

91
00:04:21.368 --> 00:04:23.161
♪ ♪

92
00:04:35.507 --> 00:04:38.093
(ambient nature sounds)

93
00:04:47.852 --> 00:04:50.981
(vehicle engine starts)

94
00:04:52.482 --> 00:04:55.193
- (vehicle drives off)
- (dog barking)

95
00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:03.076
(alarm beeping)

96
00:05:03.159 --> 00:05:05.912
- (knocks at door)
- Sarah: Alarm.

97
00:05:05.996 --> 00:05:08.373
- (Joel grunting)
- Sarah: Alarm!

98
00:05:08.456 --> 00:05:12.460
("Tomorrow" by Avril
Lavigne playing on radio)

99
00:05:24.848 --> 00:05:26.725
- Where's the pancake mix?
- Joel: Oh. was I...

100
00:05:26.808 --> 00:05:28.143
Yeah. I was. Sorry.

101
00:05:28.226 --> 00:05:29.894
I was gonna make you
birthday pancakes.

102
00:05:29.978 --> 00:05:31.229
(softly): I swear.

103
00:05:31.312 --> 00:05:33.732
You know I don't
really like pancakes.

104
00:05:33.815 --> 00:05:36.317
I know you don't like them.
It was for my benefit.

105
00:05:39.696 --> 00:05:41.406
Vitamin C.

106
00:05:50.331 --> 00:05:53.376
You get your. uh. homework done?

107
00:05:54.377 --> 00:05:56.546
- Fractions?
- (chuckling)

108
00:05:58.631 --> 00:05:59.924
How old are you again?

109
00:06:00.008 --> 00:06:01.760
Thirty-six.

110
00:06:01.843 --> 00:06:02.945
Gonna have to wear diapers soon.

111
00:06:02.969 --> 00:06:04.554
Who says I don't already?

112
00:06:07.932 --> 00:06:08.767
Shell.

113
00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:09.684
Calcium.

114
00:06:09.768 --> 00:06:12.187
Joel: Lovely.

115
00:06:12.270 --> 00:06:14.773
(garage door opening) - Is
there enough for Uncle Tommy?

116
00:06:14.856 --> 00:06:16.191
Well. there would've been.

117
00:06:17.859 --> 00:06:18.985
Ay!

118
00:06:19.069 --> 00:06:20.421
You're still alive.
you old fucker.

119
00:06:20.445 --> 00:06:21.237
Aw. he loves you.

120
00:06:21.321 --> 00:06:24.032
He's dependent on me.
Not the same.

121
00:06:24.115 --> 00:06:26.177
- I think it's the same.
- Tommy: It's definitely the same.

122
00:06:26.201 --> 00:06:28.703
I thought we was
havin' pancakes.

123
00:06:28.787 --> 00:06:30.264
We'll pick you somethin' up
on the road.

124
00:06:30.288 --> 00:06:32.350
- Concrete guys gonna be there?
- Yeah. they said maybe.

125
00:06:32.374 --> 00:06:33.208
Maybe?
We can't frame until we pour.

126
00:06:33.291 --> 00:06:35.460
We're not gettin' paid
until we frame.

127
00:06:35.543 --> 00:06:36.294
Well. we could bring
someone else on.

128
00:06:36.377 --> 00:06:38.296
- get the job done faster.
- No. no.

129
00:06:38.379 --> 00:06:39.297
I'm not splittin' this job.

130
00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:40.965
I barely wanna
split it with you.

131
00:06:41.049 --> 00:06:42.342
We could work a double.

132
00:06:42.425 --> 00:06:44.969
- Literally? Today?
- I know. I'd be done by nine.

133
00:06:45.053 --> 00:06:46.471
By nine. right?

134
00:06:47.305 --> 00:06:49.265
Yeah.

135
00:06:49.349 --> 00:06:51.101
I'll bring back a cake.

136
00:06:51.184 --> 00:06:52.227
I promise.

137
00:06:54.729 --> 00:06:57.148
Reporter (on radio): <i>...continued
disturbances in Jakarta.</i>

138
00:06:57.232 --> 00:06:58.608
<i>but are advising
U.S. citizens...</i>

139
00:06:58.691 --> 00:07:00.735
Jakarta.
Where is that. Middle East?

140
00:07:00.819 --> 00:07:02.838
Tommy: Doesn't ring a
bell. It's definitely a country.

141
00:07:02.862 --> 00:07:05.073
- Or maybe part of Asia?
- Jakarta isn't a country.

142
00:07:05.156 --> 00:07:07.718
Being a part of Asia isn't mutually
exclusive with being a country.

143
00:07:07.742 --> 00:07:09.994
and in fact. it's the
capital of Indonesia.

144
00:07:10.078 --> 00:07:12.413
Tommy: Shit. Hope for us yet.

145
00:07:12.497 --> 00:07:14.332
(microwave beeping)

146
00:07:19.129 --> 00:07:21.005
All right.

147
00:07:21.089 --> 00:07:22.549
Finish up quick.
we'll drop you off.

148
00:07:22.632 --> 00:07:25.385
- I'm still eating my eggshells.
- You got seven minutes.

149
00:07:25.468 --> 00:07:27.262
Your t-shirt's inside out.

150
00:07:30.431 --> 00:07:31.766
Shit.

151
00:07:34.394 --> 00:07:37.438
He's losin' it.

152
00:07:49.075 --> 00:07:51.411
(turns fan off)

153
00:08:03.131 --> 00:08:06.217
(light music plays)

154
00:08:16.519 --> 00:08:18.688
- (car honks)
- Joel (shouts): Sarah!

155
00:08:24.903 --> 00:08:26.613
Mr. Adler: Hey. neighbor!

156
00:08:26.696 --> 00:08:27.739
Oh. hi.

157
00:08:27.822 --> 00:08:29.824
Uh. Connie was askin' after you.

158
00:08:29.908 --> 00:08:32.285
since you haven't
been over in a while.

159
00:08:32.368 --> 00:08:34.746
Make 'em happy.

160
00:08:34.829 --> 00:08:37.665
I could come by after
school. but just for. like.

161
00:08:37.749 --> 00:08:39.709
- a little bit?
- Oh. she'll take whatcha got.

162
00:08:39.792 --> 00:08:42.712
Y'all can bake. whatever.

163
00:08:42.795 --> 00:08:44.255
Speakin' of...

164
00:08:44.339 --> 00:08:45.882
we got a lotta extra here.

165
00:08:45.965 --> 00:08:48.092
Y'all. y'all want some biscuits?

166
00:08:48.176 --> 00:08:50.303
Dad. you love biscuits.

167
00:08:54.599 --> 00:08:55.016
I do.

168
00:08:55.099 --> 00:08:57.602
But I'm on Atkins.

169
00:08:57.685 --> 00:09:00.313
- Mr. Adler: On what now?
- It's. uh... You know what?

170
00:09:00.396 --> 00:09:01.272
We gotta run.
but Sarah'll be by later.

171
00:09:01.356 --> 00:09:04.525
She'll stay as long as you want.

172
00:09:04.609 --> 00:09:05.443
Tell ya all about Atkins.

173
00:09:05.526 --> 00:09:08.947
Mr. Adler:
Great! I'll let Connie know.

174
00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:10.073
Solid.

175
00:09:13.451 --> 00:09:16.180
Can't tell you how exciting it was
listenin' to that fuckin' conversation.

176
00:09:16.204 --> 00:09:18.623
Put that out.

177
00:09:18.706 --> 00:09:20.041
Happy birthday to you.

178
00:09:20.124 --> 00:09:21.709
(engine starts)

179
00:09:30.426 --> 00:09:33.554
Want you to write this
diagram out exactly as I have it.

180
00:09:33.638 --> 00:09:36.140
Always subject and predicate.

181
00:09:36.224 --> 00:09:38.434
Verb and noun.

182
00:09:38.518 --> 00:09:41.938
Okay. the sentence is. "Where
are you going?" Subject is you.

183
00:09:42.021 --> 00:09:44.440
You... are going.

184
00:09:44.524 --> 00:09:45.024
Predicate.

185
00:09:45.108 --> 00:09:46.859
Where. adverb.

186
00:09:46.943 --> 00:09:50.321
You see it? Okay. Have
some nods. shaking of heads.

187
00:09:50.405 --> 00:09:51.423
I swear you will use this
later in life.

188
00:09:51.447 --> 00:09:53.241
Believe me.
that's why you're here.

189
00:09:53.324 --> 00:09:56.327
Okay? So... (muffled)

190
00:09:56.411 --> 00:09:57.078
(teacher fades out)

191
00:09:57.161 --> 00:10:00.164
(student coughs)

192
00:10:00.248 --> 00:10:01.833
(bell rings)

193
00:10:01.916 --> 00:10:03.435
Mrs. Lauterstein:
Yes. you need to know this!

194
00:10:03.459 --> 00:10:06.296
Yes. it's on
your test next week!

195
00:10:06.379 --> 00:10:10.091
Homework is due
end of class tomorrow!

196
00:10:10.717 --> 00:10:12.927
(indistinct chatter)

197
00:10:15.972 --> 00:10:18.808
(dog barking)

198
00:10:27.567 --> 00:10:29.152
(car honks)

199
00:10:52.925 --> 00:10:56.763
(pop music playing in store)

200
00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:05.938
Twenty.

201
00:11:06.022 --> 00:11:07.065
Sarah: That's it?

202
00:11:07.148 --> 00:11:09.359
Okay. 30.

203
00:11:09.442 --> 00:11:10.442
Twenty's good.

204
00:11:10.485 --> 00:11:13.655
It's a spring.
I'll do it right now.

205
00:11:13.738 --> 00:11:14.781
(phone ringing)

206
00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:21.454
♪ ♪

207
00:11:26.376 --> 00:11:28.461
(sirens wailing)

208
00:11:31.381 --> 00:11:33.591
Nasir: All day. I swear.

209
00:11:37.345 --> 00:11:39.138
- We're closing.
- Nasir: Huh?

210
00:11:39.222 --> 00:11:40.098
(speaks Arabic)

211
00:11:40.181 --> 00:11:41.099
We're done for today.

212
00:11:41.182 --> 00:11:46.687
- It's 3:15. we close at 7.
- (speaking Arabic)

213
00:11:46.771 --> 00:11:48.248
- I'm very sorry. He cannot finish.
- Nasir: I'm already finished.

214
00:11:48.272 --> 00:11:50.650
(speaking Arabic)

215
00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:54.695
You should go home.

216
00:11:56.197 --> 00:11:57.782
(door chimes)

217
00:12:01.494 --> 00:12:03.538
(birds cawing)

218
00:12:07.208 --> 00:12:09.252
(doorbell rings)

219
00:12:13.714 --> 00:12:15.967
- There you are. sweetie.
- Sorry.

220
00:12:16.050 --> 00:12:16.843
I was gettin' worried.

221
00:12:16.926 --> 00:12:19.512
I was getting
something for my dad.

222
00:12:19.971 --> 00:12:21.222
Hi. Mercy.

223
00:12:23.307 --> 00:12:26.811
Hey. is everything okay?
Like. on the news?

224
00:12:26.894 --> 00:12:28.688
Mrs. Adler: Like what. hon?

225
00:12:28.771 --> 00:12:32.233
Well. no. there was just a lot of
police and stuff on the road today.

226
00:12:32.316 --> 00:12:34.068
Well. that's true
every day. innit?

227
00:12:34.152 --> 00:12:36.612
People out there need
to get right with Jesus.

228
00:12:36.696 --> 00:12:39.657
Three nails. plus one
cross. equals four-given.

229
00:12:41.701 --> 00:12:43.786
I was thinkin' we'd
make some cookies.

230
00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:45.496
Chocolate chip?

231
00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:48.624
Raisin.

232
00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:56.549
C'mon. Mama.
It's green.

233
00:12:56.632 --> 00:12:59.761
- (timer buzzing)
- You love that. Oh!

234
00:12:59.844 --> 00:13:00.678
Here we go!

235
00:13:00.761 --> 00:13:04.140
(sighs) I don't know
why I talk to her.

236
00:13:04.223 --> 00:13:06.184
She's completely deaf.

237
00:13:08.227 --> 00:13:10.062
(buzzing stops)

238
00:13:34.629 --> 00:13:36.069
Mrs. Adler: You
wanna give me a hand?

239
00:13:36.130 --> 00:13:37.215
Be right there!

240
00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:00.905
Hey. Mrs. Adler?

241
00:14:00.988 --> 00:14:02.615
Could I borrow this?

242
00:14:03.157 --> 00:14:04.200
Oh!

243
00:14:05.326 --> 00:14:06.827
(chuckles)
Yeah. sure.

244
00:14:06.911 --> 00:14:09.580
It's one of Danny's.

245
00:14:09.664 --> 00:14:11.517
You know what? My dad's
gonna be back real soon.

246
00:14:11.541 --> 00:14:13.334
- I should go.
- You sure?

247
00:14:13.417 --> 00:14:15.920
- Yeah.
- Well. you're takin' some cookies.

248
00:14:27.515 --> 00:14:29.559
(Mercy whimpering)

249
00:14:51.872 --> 00:14:54.500
- (dog barking)
- (rumbling)

250
00:15:04.969 --> 00:15:07.406
Reporter (on TV): <i>No comment
today from the Austin Police Department</i>

251
00:15:07.430 --> 00:15:10.516
<i>regarding a rash of violent
incidents across the city.</i>

252
00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:13.853
<i>some suggesting a new
street drug may be to blame.</i>

253
00:15:13.936 --> 00:15:15.354
<i>More on that when we return.</i>

254
00:15:15.438 --> 00:15:17.398
<i>with Manuela Sanchez
reporting live...</i>

255
00:15:17.481 --> 00:15:19.233
- (keys jingling)
- (doorknob jiggling)

256
00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:26.824
You locked the door for once.

257
00:15:26.907 --> 00:15:28.367
Good job.

258
00:15:28.451 --> 00:15:29.368
Yeah.

259
00:15:29.452 --> 00:15:31.537
(turns TV off)

260
00:15:32.622 --> 00:15:33.497
(groans)

261
00:15:33.581 --> 00:15:36.292
- It's 10.
- I know.

262
00:15:36.375 --> 00:15:40.671
They... gave us the
wrong size for the headers.

263
00:15:40.755 --> 00:15:43.507
That doesn't mean
anything to ya. I'm sorry.

264
00:15:43.591 --> 00:15:45.468
Where's the cake?

265
00:15:45.551 --> 00:15:46.552
- Shit.
- C'mon. man.

266
00:15:46.636 --> 00:15:49.013
I'll get us one tomorrow.

267
00:15:49.096 --> 00:15:52.266
Swear. or you don't
get your present.

268
00:15:52.350 --> 00:15:55.019
- You got me a present?
- Swear.

269
00:15:55.102 --> 00:15:56.145
On my life.

270
00:16:03.903 --> 00:16:06.947
Wow.

271
00:16:08.991 --> 00:16:10.576
Fixed it for you.

272
00:16:17.583 --> 00:16:18.876
- Did you?
- What?

273
00:16:18.959 --> 00:16:20.319
- I don't hear anything.
- (scoffs)

274
00:16:20.378 --> 00:16:22.672
- (laughs)
- That was lame.

275
00:16:22.755 --> 00:16:25.883
- You're lame.
- Yeah. I know.

276
00:16:25.966 --> 00:16:27.885
Where'd you get
the money for this?

277
00:16:27.968 --> 00:16:29.720
Drugs.
I sell hardcore drugs.

278
00:16:29.804 --> 00:16:30.971
It's better than what I do.

279
00:16:31.055 --> 00:16:33.933
It was only $20.
which I stole from you.

280
00:16:34.016 --> 00:16:37.061
I could've stolen 60.
but I put the change back

281
00:16:37.144 --> 00:16:37.895
- because I'm an honest thief.
- Mm.

282
00:16:37.978 --> 00:16:40.648
Besides. it's the
thought that counts.

283
00:16:40.731 --> 00:16:42.611
And you were never gonna
do it for yourself. so.

284
00:16:47.988 --> 00:16:49.073
Thank you.

285
00:16:51.992 --> 00:16:53.619
Oh! There's one more.

286
00:16:55.996 --> 00:16:59.166
- Borrowed it from the Adlers.
- Oh. this is the one with the deleted scenes.

287
00:16:59.250 --> 00:17:01.335
Yeah. imagine how
bad those have to be.

288
00:17:01.419 --> 00:17:04.380
C'mon. pop it in. While
it's still your birthday.

289
00:17:04.463 --> 00:17:06.006
(Joel groans)

290
00:17:10.344 --> 00:17:13.222
(groans)

291
00:17:13.305 --> 00:17:14.974
- Don't fall asleep.
- 'Course. I won't.

292
00:17:15.057 --> 00:17:17.518
- (turns TV on)
- It's too riveting.

293
00:17:18.728 --> 00:17:19.895
(movie playing)

294
00:17:19.979 --> 00:17:23.149
- (gunshots. explosions)
- (yelling)

295
00:17:24.567 --> 00:17:27.403
(phone vibrating)

296
00:17:38.873 --> 00:17:39.790
(softly):
Hello?

297
00:17:39.874 --> 00:17:40.458
Tommy (on phone): <i>Joel. it's me.</i>

298
00:17:40.541 --> 00:17:43.461
<i>Uh. I'm okay.</i>

299
00:17:43.544 --> 00:17:46.505
- Yeah?
- Tommy:<i> But I'm in jail.</i>

300
00:17:46.589 --> 00:17:48.799
- Goddammit.
- Tommy: <i>Wasn't my fault this time.</i>

301
00:17:48.883 --> 00:17:51.927
<i>I was at the bar. some guy goes
crazy. starts swingin' at a waitress.</i>

302
00:17:52.011 --> 00:17:53.739
<i>I stepped in. knocked
him out. cops show up...</i>

303
00:17:53.763 --> 00:17:55.031
<i>Look. it doesn't fuckin' matter.</i>

304
00:17:55.055 --> 00:17:56.557
- <i>You gotta bail me out.</i>
- Now?

305
00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:58.201
Tommy: <i>It's Friday. you
don't get me out tonight.</i>

306
00:17:58.225 --> 00:17:59.643
<i>I'm in here all weekend.</i>

307
00:17:59.727 --> 00:18:01.312
<i>It's a fuckin' madhouse. Joel.</i>

308
00:18:01.395 --> 00:18:03.814
- <i>I gotta get out.</i>
- Well. which jail? Travis County?

309
00:18:03.898 --> 00:18:05.274
Tommy: <i>Yeah. on 10th.</i>

310
00:18:05.357 --> 00:18:08.569
- Goddammit. Tommy.
- Tommy:<i> I'm sorry.</i>

311
00:18:08.652 --> 00:18:10.780
- (sighs)
- Tommy:<i> Please.</i>

312
00:18:11.447 --> 00:18:12.656
Okay.

313
00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:15.117
- Fuckin' idiot.
- (hangs up)

314
00:18:40.184 --> 00:18:41.727
(door shuts)

315
00:18:45.439 --> 00:18:47.316
(helicopters hovering)

316
00:18:55.241 --> 00:18:57.743
- (sirens wailing)
- (dull boom)

317
00:18:57.827 --> 00:19:00.037
- (dog barking)
- (dull boom)

318
00:19:00.121 --> 00:19:04.542
- (helicopters nearing)
- (car alarm sounds)

319
00:19:06.794 --> 00:19:08.838
(house rattling)

320
00:19:17.638 --> 00:19:18.889
Dad?

321
00:19:22.643 --> 00:19:24.687
(house rattles)

322
00:19:28.023 --> 00:19:29.733
Dad?!

323
00:19:29.817 --> 00:19:32.945
(unsettling music plays)

324
00:19:37.116 --> 00:19:40.286
- (tires screeching)
- (vehicle accelerating)

325
00:19:44.707 --> 00:19:46.083
(turns TV on)

326
00:19:46.166 --> 00:19:47.877
- (TV beeps)
- Voice (on TV):<i> ...indoors.</i>

327
00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:49.712
<i>Law enforcement
and emergency services</i>

328
00:19:49.795 --> 00:19:53.090
<i>are in the area and will be in
contact with further instructions.</i>

329
00:19:53.173 --> 00:19:53.465
- (loud thud)
- (gasps)

330
00:19:53.549 --> 00:19:55.759
(barking)

331
00:19:55.843 --> 00:19:57.803
<i>Stay indoors. law enforcement...</i>

332
00:19:58.721 --> 00:20:00.806
(Mercy whimpering)

333
00:20:02.016 --> 00:20:06.896
Shh. shh... Easy.
Easy. Mercy.

334
00:20:07.688 --> 00:20:09.773
What're you doing out here. boy?

335
00:20:09.857 --> 00:20:11.901
♪ ♪

336
00:20:15.195 --> 00:20:15.696
(barks)

337
00:20:15.779 --> 00:20:18.574
(helicopters passing)

338
00:20:27.541 --> 00:20:30.336
♪ ♪

339
00:20:32.755 --> 00:20:34.340
(barking)

340
00:20:36.467 --> 00:20:38.636
- (Mercy whimpering)
- C'mon. let's get you home.

341
00:20:38.719 --> 00:20:41.221
(sirens wailing)

342
00:20:42.890 --> 00:20:45.309
- C'mon. Mercy. Please.
- (whimpers)

343
00:20:45.392 --> 00:20:48.437
Mercy!

344
00:20:49.730 --> 00:20:51.774
♪ ♪

345
00:20:53.692 --> 00:20:56.737
(clanking)

346
00:20:57.571 --> 00:21:00.616
Mrs. Adler?

347
00:21:19.426 --> 00:21:20.803
Mrs. Adler?

348
00:21:22.638 --> 00:21:24.223
(clanking)

349
00:21:25.766 --> 00:21:27.393
(distant barking)

350
00:21:37.486 --> 00:21:40.531
- (distant bang)
- (car alarm sounds)

351
00:21:40.614 --> 00:21:42.241
(heavy breathing)

352
00:21:47.496 --> 00:21:49.081
(clanking)

353
00:21:50.457 --> 00:21:52.084
Mrs. Adler?

354
00:21:56.380 --> 00:21:57.423
♪ ♪

355
00:22:06.140 --> 00:22:07.725
(softly): Help me.

356
00:22:11.270 --> 00:22:12.354
(Mr. Adler groaning)

357
00:22:19.987 --> 00:22:22.614
(raspy. heavy breathing)

358
00:22:31.457 --> 00:22:34.084
(breathing continues)

359
00:22:39.798 --> 00:22:41.842
♪ ♪

360
00:22:42.968 --> 00:22:45.554
(breathing quickens)

361
00:22:46.430 --> 00:22:49.516
(Nana gasps. screams)

362
00:22:51.852 --> 00:22:53.437
(panting)

363
00:22:55.647 --> 00:22:58.108
(tires screeching)

364
00:22:58.192 --> 00:23:00.569
(yells): Get in the
truck! Right now!

365
00:23:00.652 --> 00:23:02.404
- Move!
- (Nana snarling)

366
00:23:02.488 --> 00:23:04.656
- (bones crack)
- (grunts)

367
00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:07.785
(tense music plays)

368
00:23:08.702 --> 00:23:10.579
(Nana gasps)

369
00:23:10.662 --> 00:23:12.164
(panting)

370
00:23:13.373 --> 00:23:13.665
(yells):
What are we doin'. Joel?

371
00:23:13.749 --> 00:23:16.335
(panting)

372
00:23:16.418 --> 00:23:19.463
- (Joel grunts)
- (thud)

373
00:23:30.891 --> 00:23:33.268
- You killed her.
- Baby. I'm sorry.

374
00:23:33.352 --> 00:23:35.038
- Joel. we gotta go.
- Joel: Sarah. listen to me.

375
00:23:35.062 --> 00:23:36.855
It's not just the Adlers.

376
00:23:36.939 --> 00:23:37.606
But we're gonna be brave.

377
00:23:37.689 --> 00:23:39.400
and we're gonna get outta this.

378
00:23:39.483 --> 00:23:41.318
- (explosion)
- Hey. Let's go. Come on.

379
00:23:42.903 --> 00:23:44.196
Joel: Get in.

380
00:23:44.905 --> 00:23:47.324
Denise: Joel?

381
00:23:47.407 --> 00:23:49.135
(yells): Denise. you get
back inside the house!

382
00:23:49.159 --> 00:23:51.440
- You lock your doors! Now!
- Tommy: C'mon. c'mon. get in!

383
00:23:54.123 --> 00:23:56.208
(tires screeching)

384
00:24:01.255 --> 00:24:02.895
- Get your seat belt on.
- Tommy: Hold on.

385
00:24:02.923 --> 00:24:04.591
(accelerates)

386
00:24:04.675 --> 00:24:06.844
- (grunts)
- (thuds)

387
00:24:06.927 --> 00:24:08.011
Denise: Jesus Christ. Joel!

388
00:24:08.095 --> 00:24:10.931
(distant explosions)

389
00:24:12.808 --> 00:24:14.893
- Joel: You take 70...
- Tommy: 71. I know.

390
00:24:14.977 --> 00:24:17.062
(sirens wailing)

391
00:24:22.985 --> 00:24:24.945
- Daddy...
- We don't know.

392
00:24:25.028 --> 00:24:26.256
Tommy:
They're saying it's a virus.

393
00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:27.447
Some kind of parasite.

394
00:24:27.531 --> 00:24:29.032
Sarah: Is it from terrorists?

395
00:24:29.116 --> 00:24:31.743
We don't know.

396
00:24:31.827 --> 00:24:33.954
- Sarah: Are we sick?
- Joel: No. Of course not.

397
00:24:34.037 --> 00:24:35.390
- (radio static)
- Why did things blow up?

398
00:24:35.414 --> 00:24:37.624
No cellphone. no radio.

399
00:24:37.708 --> 00:24:38.417
Minute ago.
newsman wouldn't shut up.

400
00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:40.210
- Sarah: How do you know?
- Joel: What?

401
00:24:40.294 --> 00:24:43.380
How do you know we're not sick?

402
00:24:43.463 --> 00:24:46.008
Tommy: They're saying
it's mostly people in the city.

403
00:24:46.091 --> 00:24:48.010
That's why they got
the highway blocked off.

404
00:24:51.597 --> 00:24:52.055
God.

405
00:24:52.139 --> 00:24:54.766
It's Jimmy's place.

406
00:24:59.479 --> 00:25:00.522
♪ ♪

407
00:25:03.859 --> 00:25:06.236
The Adlers would take
Nana into the city.

408
00:25:06.320 --> 00:25:07.946
To the hospital for stuff.

409
00:25:08.030 --> 00:25:10.991
That's right. They would.
That's probably why.

410
00:25:12.534 --> 00:25:17.164
But... you'd have
to go a lot... right?

411
00:25:17.247 --> 00:25:17.789
We're fine. Trust me.

412
00:25:17.873 --> 00:25:21.126
(distant sirens)

413
00:25:22.586 --> 00:25:24.213
(softly): All right.

414
00:25:28.383 --> 00:25:30.886
Father: Here! Right here!

415
00:25:30.969 --> 00:25:32.512
- Hey!
- What are you doin'?

416
00:25:32.596 --> 00:25:35.307
- Got a kid. Joel.
- So do we. Keep driving.

417
00:25:35.390 --> 00:25:37.076
- (father pleading)
- We could put them in the back.

418
00:25:37.100 --> 00:25:40.646
(voice fades out)

419
00:25:40.729 --> 00:25:42.606
Somebody else'll come along.

420
00:25:50.239 --> 00:25:53.116
- (accelerates)
- (cars honking)

421
00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:55.494
Fuck! Everybody had
the same fuckin' idea.

422
00:25:55.577 --> 00:25:57.013
- (honking)
- I can't get through this.

423
00:25:57.037 --> 00:25:59.641
All right. all right. Let's think it
through. we'll think it through.

424
00:25:59.665 --> 00:26:01.267
- Tommy: Fuck!
- Joel: All right. take the field.

425
00:26:01.291 --> 00:26:03.186
We cut across and we pick
up on the. on the west side.

426
00:26:03.210 --> 00:26:03.961
Yeah. yeah. yeah. yeah.
West. west. all right.

427
00:26:04.044 --> 00:26:06.129
All right. hang on.

428
00:26:19.476 --> 00:26:21.728
Shit! Fuckin' army.

429
00:26:21.812 --> 00:26:23.581
- Isn't that good?
- Tommy: It's good for them.

430
00:26:23.605 --> 00:26:25.649
but that's the highway
we're tryin' to get to.

431
00:26:25.732 --> 00:26:27.210
Joel: All right. keep
movin'. Head north.

432
00:26:27.234 --> 00:26:28.920
- Could be a lot of people.
- Joel: Well. we can't go south.

433
00:26:28.944 --> 00:26:30.570
we can't go east.
we can't go west.

434
00:26:30.654 --> 00:26:32.531
Hell else we supposed to go?

435
00:26:33.240 --> 00:26:34.324
Tommy. come on!

436
00:26:35.117 --> 00:26:36.743
(tires screeching)

437
00:26:39.663 --> 00:26:41.206
Yeah.

438
00:26:41.290 --> 00:26:42.124
Yeah. I know that place.

439
00:26:42.207 --> 00:26:43.750
- This can work.
- Yeah. but then what?

440
00:26:43.834 --> 00:26:46.545
I don't know. Mexico.
Just far. far as we can.

441
00:26:46.628 --> 00:26:48.839
- How much gas?
- Three-quarter tank.

442
00:26:48.922 --> 00:26:52.342
Go through town. golf course
by the river. straight across.

443
00:26:52.426 --> 00:26:54.746
we pick up the highway on
the other side of the blockade...

444
00:26:55.262 --> 00:26:58.307
then we're out.

445
00:26:59.766 --> 00:27:02.602
(intense music plays)

446
00:27:04.730 --> 00:27:06.356
Maybe it's everywhere.

447
00:27:07.482 --> 00:27:10.152
Maybe there's nowhere to go.

448
00:27:15.073 --> 00:27:16.825
What the fuck?!

449
00:27:16.908 --> 00:27:18.452
(loud rumbling)

450
00:27:29.338 --> 00:27:31.423
Tommy: Son of a
bitch. Gotta go around.

451
00:27:31.506 --> 00:27:32.591
Grab somethin'!

452
00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:36.136
(tires screeching)

453
00:27:37.512 --> 00:27:39.514
(people screaming)

454
00:27:39.598 --> 00:27:40.640
♪ ♪

455
00:27:48.148 --> 00:27:49.816
All right. keep goin'.
keep goin'.

456
00:27:49.900 --> 00:27:51.526
- Shit. Tommy!
- (tires screeching)

457
00:27:51.610 --> 00:27:53.195
(car honks)

458
00:27:54.404 --> 00:27:56.948
Tommy. you can't stop here.

459
00:27:57.032 --> 00:27:58.634
- I can't drive through 'em all.
- Are you serious?!

460
00:27:58.658 --> 00:27:59.493
Just keep goin'!

461
00:27:59.576 --> 00:28:03.038
- (glass shatters)
- (people screaming)

462
00:28:05.165 --> 00:28:06.416
Go. go. go.
Back. back. back.

463
00:28:06.500 --> 00:28:08.168
- back. back. back. back!
- I'm trying!

464
00:28:13.006 --> 00:28:14.424
Joel: Tommy. go
faster! We gotta go!

465
00:28:14.508 --> 00:28:15.651
Tommy: I'm tryin'!
There's nowhere to fuckin' go!

466
00:28:15.675 --> 00:28:17.236
- Joel: Find an alley!
- Tommy: What alley?!

467
00:28:17.260 --> 00:28:18.780
- There's people everywhere!
- Joel: Roll the fuck over them!

468
00:28:18.804 --> 00:28:20.263
We gotta get
off this street now!

469
00:28:20.347 --> 00:28:21.657
Tommy: That's what
I'm tryin' to do. Joel.

470
00:28:21.681 --> 00:28:23.475
Joel: We're gonna be
okay. Just keep drivin'.

471
00:28:23.558 --> 00:28:25.602
Dad?!

472
00:28:25.685 --> 00:28:26.978
Holy shit!

473
00:28:27.687 --> 00:28:29.898
Move... move!

474
00:28:29.981 --> 00:28:31.817
(plane approaching)

475
00:28:34.194 --> 00:28:35.779
(explosion)

476
00:28:45.330 --> 00:28:48.500
- (muffled booms)
- (car alarm blaring)

477
00:28:55.882 --> 00:28:57.676
(Joel grunting)

478
00:28:58.385 --> 00:29:01.221
(heavy breathing)

479
00:29:01.721 --> 00:29:04.266
Sarah... Sarah.

480
00:29:04.349 --> 00:29:05.725
Stay right there.
Don't move.

481
00:29:07.018 --> 00:29:08.478
Tommy. you okay?

482
00:29:08.562 --> 00:29:09.312
Tommy: Yeah. I'm okay.

483
00:29:09.396 --> 00:29:12.232
(breathing heavily)

484
00:29:15.902 --> 00:29:17.237
(groans)

485
00:29:23.410 --> 00:29:25.745
Joel: Sarah... don't look.

486
00:29:25.829 --> 00:29:27.706
You look at me... okay?

487
00:29:27.789 --> 00:29:29.559
- I'm sorry. baby. I know. I know.
- (Sarah wincing)

488
00:29:29.583 --> 00:29:30.959
Come here.
Put your arms around me.

489
00:29:31.042 --> 00:29:33.003
Come here. come here.

490
00:29:33.086 --> 00:29:35.797
I got you.
I got... I got you.

491
00:29:35.881 --> 00:29:38.091
Got you.

492
00:29:38.175 --> 00:29:40.177
- (Sarah grunting)
- Are you okay?

493
00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:40.927
- Mm-mm.
- Are you okay?

494
00:29:41.011 --> 00:29:43.096
- My ankle.
- All right. okay.

495
00:29:43.180 --> 00:29:44.681
We gotta get off the street!

496
00:29:44.764 --> 00:29:46.391
- (siren wailing)
- Shit!

497
00:29:49.728 --> 00:29:51.188
(shouts): Tommy?!

498
00:29:51.271 --> 00:29:53.023
Tommy?!

499
00:29:53.106 --> 00:29:55.859
Tommy!

500
00:29:55.942 --> 00:29:58.778
Head to the river!
I'll find a way.

501
00:29:58.862 --> 00:30:00.614
Get her outta here. Joel! Go!

502
00:30:02.157 --> 00:30:03.509
- We can't leave him.
- He'll be fine.

503
00:30:03.533 --> 00:30:05.160
- Can you run?
- No.

504
00:30:05.994 --> 00:30:07.871
- You keep your eyes on me.
- Okay.

505
00:30:07.954 --> 00:30:08.705
- Okay?
